<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="188" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1504,2013]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,1504,1528]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body (
<figureCitation box="[348,426,1504,1527]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="3.[151,255,972,996]" captionTargetBox="[210,1358,256,857]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,247,948]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 13. Alapona modesta sp. nov., male holotype, body in dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217749/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
Fig. 
<number box="[399,426,1504,1527]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
) brown with small black or dark brown maculae on head, pronotum and forewings; body not strongly dorsoventrally flattened; transocular width (
<figureCitation box="[713,775,1539,1562]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1878,1902]" captionTargetBox="[226,1334,194,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[226,1334,194,1824]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Alapona modesta sp. nov., male holotype. 1, anterior portion of body, dorsal view. 2, head, frontal view. 3, anterior portion of body, lateral view. 4, forewing. 5, sternite VIII, ventral view. 6, pygofer, lateral view. 7, subgenital plate, ventral view. 8, connective and styles, dorsal view. 9, style, lateral view. 10 – 12, aedeagus in lateral, dorsal, and caudal views, respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217748/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
Fig. 
<number box="[763,775,1539,1562]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
) narrower than maximum pronotum width; each ocellus (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1878,1902]" captionTargetBox="[226,1334,194,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[226,1334,194,1824]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Alapona modesta sp. nov., male holotype. 1, anterior portion of body, dorsal view. 2, head, frontal view. 3, anterior portion of body, lateral view. 4, forewing. 5, sternite VIII, ventral view. 6, pygofer, lateral view. 7, subgenital plate, ventral view. 8, connective and styles, dorsal view. 9, style, lateral view. 10 – 12, aedeagus in lateral, dorsal, and caudal views, respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217748/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,163,1573,1596]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
) closer to adjacent eye than to midline and equidistant from anterior and posterior margins; crown-frons transition (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1878,1902]" captionTargetBox="[226,1334,194,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[226,1334,194,1824]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Alapona modesta sp. nov., male holotype. 1, anterior portion of body, dorsal view. 2, head, frontal view. 3, anterior portion of body, lateral view. 4, forewing. 5, sternite VIII, ventral view. 6, pygofer, lateral view. 7, subgenital plate, ventral view. 8, connective and styles, dorsal view. 9, style, lateral view. 10 – 12, aedeagus in lateral, dorsal, and caudal views, respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217748/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,164,1608,1631]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
) thick, not foliaceous, with longitudinal striae; forewing without supernumerary veins* (
<figureCitation box="[1117,1184,1608,1631]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1878,1902]" captionTargetBox="[226,1334,194,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[226,1334,194,1824]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Alapona modesta sp. nov., male holotype. 1, anterior portion of body, dorsal view. 2, head, frontal view. 3, anterior portion of body, lateral view. 4, forewing. 5, sternite VIII, ventral view. 6, pygofer, lateral view. 7, subgenital plate, ventral view. 8, connective and styles, dorsal view. 9, style, lateral view. 10 – 12, aedeagus in lateral, dorsal, and caudal views, respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217748/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
Fig. 
<number box="[1168,1184,1608,1631]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
); hind leg with femoral setal formula 
<number box="[297,313,1643,1666]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="2.0">2</number>
- 
<number box="[322,338,1643,1666]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="2.0">2</number>
- 
<number box="[346,356,1643,1666]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1.0">1</number>
*, tibia row PD with approximately twice as many cucullate setae as in AD*; AD with 
<number box="[1280,1315,1643,1666]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">
2- 
<specimenCount box="[1301,1315,1643,1666]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" type="intercalary">4</specimenCount>
</number>
intercalary setae between cucullate macrosetae*, first tarsomere as long as combined length of two distal tarsomeres*; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[158,278,1712,1735]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1878,1902]" captionTargetBox="[226,1334,194,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[226,1334,194,1824]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Alapona modesta sp. nov., male holotype. 1, anterior portion of body, dorsal view. 2, head, frontal view. 3, anterior portion of body, lateral view. 4, forewing. 5, sternite VIII, ventral view. 6, pygofer, lateral view. 7, subgenital plate, ventral view. 8, connective and styles, dorsal view. 9, style, lateral view. 10 – 12, aedeagus in lateral, dorsal, and caudal views, respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217748/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Figs 11, 12</figureCitation>
) dorsal apodemes well developed, forming a single structure expanded laterally (resembling a pair of wings) and without processes (= paraphyses 
<emphasis box="[548,607,1747,1770]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="DeLong" box="[614,765,1747,1770]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" refString="DeLong, D. M. (1980) A new genus Alapona, a new Ponana subgenus, Peranoa, and two new species of Gyponinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Ohio Journal of Science, 80 (5), 217 - 219." type="journal article" year="1980">
DeLong 
<number box="[708,765,1747,1770]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1980.0">1980</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1504,2013]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="188" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,269,1781,1805]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Notes.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="DeLong" box="[425,594,1781,1804]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" refString="DeLong, D. M. (1980) A new genus Alapona, a new Ponana subgenus, Peranoa, and two new species of Gyponinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Ohio Journal of Science, 80 (5), 217 - 219." type="journal article" year="1980">
DeLong (
<number box="[528,586,1781,1804]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1980.0">1980</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[606,697,1782,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Alapona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[606,697,1782,1805]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Alapona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ball, 1920" authorityName="Ball" authorityYear="1920" box="[838,1040,1781,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Ponana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[838,921,1782,1805]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Ponana</emphasis>
Ball, 
<number box="[987,1040,1781,1804]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1920.0">1920</number>
</taxonomicName>
and can be distinguished from other Gyponini genera by the following characteristics: (
<number box="[692,703,1816,1839]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1.0">1</number>
) head narrower than pronotum; (
<number box="[1056,1070,1816,1839]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="2.0">2</number>
) anterior margin of crown slightly produced and thick; (
<number box="[393,406,1851,1874]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="3.0">3</number>
) ocelli closer to eyes than to median line of crown; and (
<number box="[1074,1089,1851,1874]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="4.0">4</number>
) aedeagus without paraphyses, dorsoventrally broadened, with a broad platelike structure resembling a pair of wings. However, characters 
<number box="[1293,1306,1885,1908]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1.0">1</number>
and 
<number box="[1357,1370,1885,1908]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="2.0">2</number>
occur in several Gyponini genera, whereas character 
<date box="[651,717,1920,1943]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
<number box="[651,664,1920,1943]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="3.0">3</number>
may
</date>
vary among species in a single genus. Furthermore, as stated in the original description of 
<taxonomicName authority="DeLong 1980" authorityName="DeLong" authorityYear="1980" box="[409,684,1955,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Alapona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[409,499,1955,1978]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Alapona</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DeLong" box="[519,676,1955,1978]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" refString="DeLong, D. M. (1980) A new genus Alapona, a new Ponana subgenus, Peranoa, and two new species of Gyponinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Ohio Journal of Science, 80 (5), 217 - 219." type="journal article" year="1980">
DeLong 
<number box="[619,676,1955,1978]" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" value="1980.0">1980</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the type-species is superficially similar to species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1303,1386,1955,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Ponana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1303,1386,1955,1978]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Ponana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,228,1990,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Polana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,228,1990,2013]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Polana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, most of the external diagnostic characteristics given above cannot separate most species of these genera. Species of 
<taxonomicName box="[355,446,152,175]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Alapona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[355,446,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Alapona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can only be accurately identified based on characteristics of the aedeagus dorsal apodemes, which do not bear processes and are laterally expanded resembling a pair of wings, in caudal view (
<figureCitation box="[1213,1293,186,209]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1878,1902]" captionTargetBox="[226,1334,194,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[226,1334,194,1824]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Alapona modesta sp. nov., male holotype. 1, anterior portion of body, dorsal view. 2, head, frontal view. 3, anterior portion of body, lateral view. 4, forewing. 5, sternite VIII, ventral view. 6, pygofer, lateral view. 7, subgenital plate, ventral view. 8, connective and styles, dorsal view. 9, style, lateral view. 10 – 12, aedeagus in lateral, dorsal, and caudal views, respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217748/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
Fig. 
<number box="[1263,1293,186,209]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
It should be noted that what the present authors refer to as “processes of the dorsal apodemes” (which are absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,241,256,279]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Alapona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,241,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Alapona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were referred to as “paraphyses” by 
<bibRefCitation author="DeLong" box="[690,862,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" refString="DeLong, D. M. (1980) A new genus Alapona, a new Ponana subgenus, Peranoa, and two new species of Gyponinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Ohio Journal of Science, 80 (5), 217 - 219." type="journal article" year="1980">
DeLong (
<number box="[798,854,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" value="1980.0">1980</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
in the original genus description. However, these structures are found in the majority of Gyponini genera and, unfortunately, have not been named consistently. In related genera, these structures were independently called “aedealati” in 
<taxonomicName authority="DeLong &amp; Freytag 1967" authorityName="DeLong &amp; Freytag" authorityYear="1967" box="[867,1250,325,348]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Ponana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[867,950,325,348]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Ponana</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DeLong" box="[966,1242,325,348]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" refString="DeLong, D. M. &amp; Freytag, P. H. (1967) Studies of the world Gyponinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). A synopsis of the genus Ponana. Contributions of the American Entomological Institute, 1 (7), 1 - 86." type="journal article" year="1967">
DeLong &amp; Freytag 
<number box="[1185,1242,325,348]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" value="1967.0">1967</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, “paraphyses” in 
<taxonomicName authority="DeLong 1980" authorityName="DeLong" authorityYear="1980" box="[151,542,360,383]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Ponana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Peranoa">
<emphasis box="[151,234,360,383]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Ponana</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[255,347,360,383]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Peranoa</emphasis>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="DeLong" box="[376,535,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" refString="DeLong, D. M. (1980) A new genus Alapona, a new Ponana subgenus, Peranoa, and two new species of Gyponinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Ohio Journal of Science, 80 (5), 217 - 219." type="journal article" year="1980">
DeLong 
<number box="[478,535,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" value="1980.0">1980</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and “lateral parameres” in 
<taxonomicName authority="DeLong &amp; Freytag 1972" authorityName="DeLong &amp; Freytag" authorityYear="1972" box="[869,1261,360,383]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Polana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[869,946,360,383]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">Polana</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DeLong" box="[966,1253,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" refString="DeLong, D. M. &amp; Freytag, P. H. (1972) Studies of the world Gyponinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). The genus Polana. Arquivos de Zoologia do Estado de Sao Paulo, 22 (5), 239 - 324." type="journal article" year="1972">
DeLong &amp; Freytag 
<number box="[1196,1253,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Adding to the confusion, in the latter work, the “lateral parameres” were considered to originate either from the dorsal apodeme (= phallobase) or from the base of the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
